9":"1279","1312":"1312","1344":"1344","1278":"1278","1410":"1410","1342":"1342","after 1360":"after 1360","1308":"1308","Devonshire, England":"Devon, England, United Kingdom","Modbury, Devonshire, England":"Modbury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","Whympston, Modbury, Devonshire, England":"Modbury, Devon, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Fortescue","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): nickname from Old French <i>fort</i> ‘strong’ + <i>escu</i> ‘shield’.","History: A family of this name claim descent from Radulfus Fortescu who is recorded in Domesday Book (1086) as holding lands at Modbury (Devon)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When William Fortescue I was born in 1315, in Modbury, Devon, England, United Kingdom, his father, Adam Fortescue III, was 37 and his mother, Anna de La Porte, was 37. He married Alice de Strechleigh in 1344, in Devon, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1360, in his hometown."},"et":{"1315–after 1360":"1315–pärast 1360","1312–Male":"1312–Surnud","1314–Male":"1314–Surnud","1315–1360":"1315–1360","1325–1410":"1325–1410","1345–141